<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHN O' GROATS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I read your Sept. 22 article by Jonathan Gold in praise of the outstanding 
Westside restaurant John O' Groats with great interest, having enjoyed many of 
its excellent vegetarian dishes myself. Therefore, it was most surprising to 
find a typical Sikh diner so inaccurately described as a "hamburger-ordering 
Sikh." 
</P>
<P>
 The American Sikh community is highly visible and recognizable, because we 
usually dress in white, and both men and women wear turbans. For more than 25 
years many of us in Los Angeles have frequented Westside restaurants, and it is 
generally known and respected that we are vegetarians. Paul Tyler, whose family 
owns John O' Groats and who himself spends much of his time there, told me he 
had never seen a Sikh order a hamburger and that he too was surprised at Gold's 
use of the words hamburger-ordering to describe a Sikh. (Veggie-burger, maybe, 
but hamburger ? I don't think so!) 
</P>
<P>
 -- SAT BACHAN 
</P>
<P>
 KAUR KHALSA 
</P>
<P>
 Sikh Dharma 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
