<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; OFFICIALS GET LOOK AT MARINE CENTER PLANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRA E. STOLL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Officials from the city of Ventura, the Ventura Chamber of Commerce and the 
Ventura Port District got their first look Wednesday at architectural drawings 
for a proposed marine education center at Ventura Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
 The center, including indoor and outdoor aquariums, would be topped by eight 
five-story copper domes, said Al Fiori, a partner in Rising Hawk Productions, 
the company planning the center. The bodies of the buildings will be a 
sand-like material, to remind visitors of the shore, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "Conceptually, it's absolutely awesome," Councilwoman Rosa Lee Measures said. 
"It will be a world center that's like no other." 
</P>
<P>
 Plans call for the facility to include an outdoor shipbuilding facility, the 
aquariums, fish hatcheries, an Imax-Cinemax large screen theater and a research 
center for Jean-Michel Cousteau, the son of oceanographer Jacques Cousteau. 
</P>
<P>
 The city of Oxnard unveiled plans in July for a 100,000-square-foot aquarium 
at Channel Islands Harbor, and a $16,000 study of the proposal is being 
undertaken. Richard Parsons, general manager of the Ventura Port District, said 
the competing proposal made Ventura officials eager to move ahead quickly. 
</P>
<P>
 Fiori made the rounds Wednesday to the City Council's economics committee, the 
chamber's land-use subcommittee and the Port District Commission, which owns 
the site on which the facility would be built. 
</P>
<P>
 Fiori told the economics committee that he needed another $30,000 to add to 
the $10,000 the city has already spent to fund planning for the project. The 
chamber subcommittee recommended contributing $3,000 of chamber money. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's going to cost some sizable dollars," said Measures, saying public and 
private funding was needed to build the marine center. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council is scheduled to review the plans at 6 p.m. Monday, before its 
regular meeting, and decide whether to commit more money to the project, whose 
total cost is estimated at more than $5 million. IRA E. STOLL 
</P>
</TEXT>
