<HEADLINE>
<P>
TONIGHT'S NFL GAME; OILERS HOPE TO RETAIN SERIES EDGE AS BROWNS TRY TO KEEP 
MOMENTUM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Houston Oilers have a legacy to fulfill. The Cleveland Browns have one to 
overcome. 
</P>
<P>
 The Oilers are at the same starting point -- 1-4 -- as a season ago, when they 
won their last 11 games and their second consecutive AFC Central title. 
</P>
<P>
 The Browns are 4-1 but have a history of fading in the stretch. But they hope 
to avoid another collapse beginning tonight, when they try to beat the Oilers 
for only the second time in nine games. 
</P>
<P>
 The Browns, after three seasons of turmoil under Coach Bill Belichick, are 
beginning to see results. 
</P>
<P>
 The Browns have a 7-17 combined record in the second half of the last three 
seasons under Belichick. They started last season 5-2 and finished 2-7. In 
1992, they started 4-3 and finished 3-6. 
</P>
<P>
 Belichick now feels comfortable enough to loosen the reins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101394-0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 088163 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
October 13, 1994, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
