<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: REGION; POLICE WON'T CHARGE SCHOOLS FOR SEARCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN COX 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monterey Park officials have decided to tear up a $3,000 bill that they sent 
to Montebello Unified School District officials after city police were called 
to help search for a missing student, school officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Some Montebello Unified school board members were upset that they received the 
bill to pay for police overtime during the Sept. 19 search. 
</P>
<P>
 Monterey Park officials could not be reached and city police declined to 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
 District Supt. Darline Robles reported in a memo that city officials said they 
sent the bill because they felt the district should have responded more quickly 
when it learned that the child, a special-education student, was missing. 
</P>
<P>
 Police were called after the mother of the 10-year-old girl notified Macy 
Intermediate School in Monterey Park that the student had failed to board a bus 
after school. The girl was found unharmed about 12 hours later. JOHN COX 
</P>
</TEXT>
