improvements to prepare for auto makers' lower-emission cars, mandated by the 
state Air Resources Board. The consumer groups had objected to the way 
ratepayers would have been required to pay for the improvements. Under the 
compromise, also approved by the South Coast Air Quality Management District 
and the Southern California Assn. of Governments, these costs will be paid back 
to utility consumers by the sixth year of the plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
